05004nam a22006135i 9781554588954DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20132013xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97815545889547 a10.51644/97815545889542doi  a(DE-B1597)667738  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPR9198.2.N4bD45 2013 7aLIT0040802bisacsh04a810.9/97182231 aDelisle, Jennifer Bowering, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Newfoundland Diaspora :bMapping the Literature of Out-Migration /cJennifer Bowering Delisle. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (220 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tMapping the Literature of Out-Migration -- tDefining the Newfoundland Diaspora -- tNewfoundland and the Concept of Diaspora -- tAffective Responses -- tDonna Morrissey and the Search for Prairie Gold -- t“The ‘Going Home Again’ Complaint”: Carl Leggo and Nostalgia for Newfoundland -- tIs the Newfoundlander “Authentic” in the Diaspora? -- tE.J. Pratt and the Gateway to Canada -- t“A Papier Mâché Rock”: Wayne Johnston and Rejecting Regionalism -- tImagining the Newfoundland Nation -- t“ This is Their Country Now”: David French, Confederation, and the Imagined Community -- tWriting the “Old Lost Land”: Johnston Part Two -- tPostmodern Ethnicity and Memoirs from Away -- tHelen Buss / Margaret Clarke and the Negotiation of Identity -- tThe “Holdin’ Ground”: David Macfarlane and the Second Generation -- tWriting in Diaspora Space -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOut-migration, driven by high unemployment and a floundering economy, has been a defining aspect of Newfoundland society for well over a century, and it reached new heights with the cod moratorium in 1992. This Newfoundland “diaspora” has had a profound impact on the province’s literature. Many writers and scholars have referred to Newfoundland out-migration as a diaspora, but few have examined the theoretical implications of applying this contested term to a predominantly inter-provincial movement of mainly white, economically motivated migrants. The Newfoundland Diaspora argues that “diaspora” helpfully references the painful displacement of a group whose members continue to identify with each other and with the “homeland.” It examines important literary works of the Newfoundland diaspora, including the poetry of E.J. Pratt, the drama of David French, the fiction of Donna Morrissey and Wayne Johnston, and the memoirs of David Macfarlane. These works are the sites of a broad inquiry into the theoretical flashpoints of affect, diasporic authenticity, nationalism, race, and ethnicity. The literature of the Newfoundland diaspora both contributes to and responds to critical movements in Canadian literature and culture, querying the place of regional, national, and ethnic affiliations in a literature drawn along the borders of the nation-state. This diaspora plays a part in defining Canada even as it looks beyond the borders of Canada as a literary community.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCanadian literaturezNewfoundland and LabradorxHistory and criticism. 0aEmigration and immigration in literature. 4aCultural Studies. 4aLiterary Criticism. 4aLiterary Criticism: Canadian Literature. 4aPolitical Science: Globalization. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Canadian.2bisacsh  aCanadian Literature.  aDiaspora.  aNewfoundland Literature.  aNewfoundland Out-Migration.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013z978311127412608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP